Product Requirements Document (PRD v3.1)

Product name: TransFitness
Version: 3.1
Status: MVP Definition
Owner: Taylor Pangilinan
Last updated: December 2025

1. Executive Summary

TransFitness is a safety first, dysphoria aware fitness app built by and for trans and non binary people. The initial product wedge focuses on transmasc and non binary users who bind, are on testosterone, and are pre or post top surgery.

The core of the product is a workout engine that understands three realities most mainstream apps ignore:

Many users are training while binding

Hormone replacement therapy changes energy, recovery, and body composition over time

Gender affirming surgeries temporarily reset what safe movement looks like

TransFitness combines this context with strength and conditioning best practices to generate personalized, binder safe, surgery aware training plans and explains the “why” behind decisions in clear, affirming language.

Alongside the workout engine, the app delivers:

Short, evidence informed guidance for training through HRT changes and surgical recovery

Space aware programming that adapts to whether a user feels safe in gyms, prefers to train at home, or only has access to low key environments

A lightweight education and Copilot layer that lets users ask questions about their training, binding, HRT, and post surgical movement, within clear safety bounds

Over time, TransFitness will expand to support transfemme and non binary users across estrogen based HRT and other surgery paths, and will add coach tooling so trans coaches can deliver programs inside the same safety framework. The long term vision is a trusted, trans led fitness layer that sits between individual coaches, local gyms, and general purpose workout apps.

2. Problem Statement

Trans and non binary people who want to move their bodies face a cluster of problems that mainstream fitness products do not address.

Unclear safety when binding and exercising

People routinely exceed recommended binder limits because dysphoria relief often outweighs abstract health warnings

There is very little practical guidance on how to modify strength and cardio sessions while binding, when to absolutely unbind, and what red flag symptoms look like

Anxiety about HRT and performance

Transmasc users on testosterone want to build strength and muscle but often do not know how to adjust volume, intensity, and recovery by month and year on T

Transfemme users starting estrogen fear losing strength or “ruining” their gains and rarely find clear, phased guidance that balances safety, performance, and goals

No structured plan to return to movement after gender affirming surgery

Post top surgery, users are told “no lifting for X weeks” then left to guess how to progress from walking to full upper body training

People are scared of damaging incisions, impacting scar healing, or causing long term issues by moving too early or too aggressively

Gyms and locker rooms feel unsafe or dysphoria inducing

Many users experience real or anticipated harm in gendered spaces like locker rooms and bathrooms

Even when they pass, anxiety around where to change, shower, or be seen keeps people from going to the gym at all

Fragmented and inconsistent information

Useful advice is scattered across Reddit, Discord, Facebook, and individual trans trainers

Users are forced to cobble together safety rules, HRT insights, and workout ideas from anecdotal threads

There is no single tool that encodes clinical guidance, lived experience, and practical training into one coherent system

TransFitness aims to become that coherent system for an initial wedge of users, then expand outward.

3. Product Pillars

The product is organized around five pillars.

Safety aware workout engine
A personalized training engine that encodes binder safety, surgery phases, HRT context, and experience level into structured workouts.

Education and reassurance layer
A content layer that answers “Why this workout and is this safe for me right now” in plain language, linked to real research and lived experience.

Space aware training modes
Programming that respects where users actually feel safe moving, from home only to community gyms and outdoors.

Community and accountability (future)
Lightweight connection features that support consistency and belonging without becoming a full social network.

Recovery and nourishment (future)
Simple, HRT and surgery aware guidance for fueling and recovering, focused on function and nervous system safety rather than dieting.

For MVP, pillars 1, 2, and a narrow slice of 3 are in scope. Pillars 4 and 5 are partially represented only through very small, text first elements.

4. MVP Scope

This section explicitly defines what is in scope for the first public MVP and what is intentionally out of scope or deferred to later phases.

4.1 MVP goals

For MVP, TransFitness will:

Prove that a safety aware, trans specific workout engine can reliably generate plans that feel relevant, affirming, and trustworthy to transmasc and non binary users who bind

Make the existing safety intelligence visible to users through “Why this workout” explanations and short, contextual education snippets

Support at least one clear journey per persona:

Training while binding

Preparing for top surgery

Early to mid post top surgery return to movement

Operate within clear safety and non medical advice boundaries, with simple deflection patterns for acute or clinical issues

4.2 In scope for MVP

Pillar 1, Safety aware workout engine

MVP includes:

Onboarding that collects:

Training environment (home, gym, studio, outdoors)

Binder status and basic binding while exercising behavior

HRT status and start date for testosterone

High level goal and experience level

Top surgery history and date, at least as a single surgery field

Workout generation that:

Uses binder behavior, HRT status, surgery status, and environment in its rules

Applies binder aware limits to volume and intensity

Applies basic top surgery phases:

Pre op training emphasis

Early post op, movement suggestions are education only

Mid post op, conservative progression patterns

Adjusts programming style based on environment and equipment (home friendly vs gym heavy)

Rules engine output that:

Records which rules fired in a structured rules_triggered field

Stores a generation_context snapshot with the workout

Pillar 2, Education and reassurance

MVP includes:

“Why this workout” explanations:

At least two or three short, human readable explanations per generated workout that reference binder safety, HRT, and surgery context when applicable

Education snippets:

Short text snippets attached to workouts for:

Binding and exercise

Early HRT training expectations for T

Early and mid post op considerations

Selection logic that shows only relevant snippets based on profile and phase

At least two small “mini guides”:

Binder safety basics

General, non prescriptive outline of returning to movement after top surgery

Pillar 3, Space aware training modes

MVP includes:

Training environment selection in onboarding

Environment aware workout generation:

Home only users receive no machine based prescriptions

Gym users can receive more varied equipment while still respecting toggles

Light guidance on training at home versus in gyms, through snippets and explanations

Copilot v0, optional but strongly preferred for MVP

A simple Copilot chat that:

Lets users ask general questions about their workouts, binding, HRT, and surgery context

Uses retrieval over your own research and guidelines

Has clear, hard coded deflections for acute symptom and medical questions

If Copilot does not make MVP, the education snippets and “Why this workout” explanations remain required.

Platform and UX

Mobile app delivered via React Native or Expo, focused on:

Onboarding

Daily workout view and execution

“Why this workout” and education snippets

Profile and settings

Basic analytics and error logging to track usage and issues

4.3 Out of scope for MVP

The following items are explicitly out of scope for MVP and will not be built before the first public test cohort.

Community and social features

No friend system or public profiles

No open social feed or comment threads

No accountability pods or group challenges

No in app DMs or messaging between users

Coach and marketplace features

No dedicated coach accounts

No coach marketplace or paid programming inside the app

No external coach dashboard or web admin tools beyond what you need for internal content management

Advanced Copilot capabilities

No long form, multi step coaching programs run entirely by Copilot

No interpretation of wearable or biomarker data

No complex mood tracking analysis beyond very basic prompts if included

Nutrition and detailed recovery

No calorie tracking or macro logging

No specific meal plans or food databases

No injury specific rehab protocols beyond very general movement guidance

No sleep tracking integrations

Transfemme specific programming

MVP will not ship dedicated transfemme or estrogen specific training tracks beyond basic education snippets

Support for transfemme users will be explicitly framed as limited, with a plan to expand in a later phase

Integrations and external services

No wearables integrations for launch

No third party gym directories or safe space maps

No automated clinician reports or provider portal

4.4 Non goals and constraints

The app will not provide medical advice or clearance for exercise, post operative activity, or HRT dosing

The app will not override surgeon or clinician instructions, and will explicitly instruct users to follow those over general rules when there is a conflict

The app will not attempt to be a general fitness product for all people, it will prioritize being excellent for the initial wedge of transmasc and non binary users who bind and are near top surgery and early T


