## 6. User Stories

These are grouped by experience area. They’re written for Jay, but generalize to the MVP wedge.

### 6.1 Onboarding & Setup

1. As a transmasc person who binds, I want onboarding questions that reflect my actual experience (binding, HRT, surgery), so I feel seen and trust the recommendations.
2. As a user who trains mostly at home, I want to select my training environment and equipment, so workouts match what I can realistically do.
3. As someone on testosterone, I want to record when I started HRT without doing math, so the app can calculate how long I’ve been on T and adjust training appropriately.
4. As someone who has had or is planning top surgery, I want a simple way to indicate my surgery type and date, so my plan respects my healing timeline.

### 6.2 Binder-aware training

5. As a person who binds regularly, I want the app to ask whether I’m binding today (or how often I bind when exercising), so it can adjust intensity and exercise selection.
6. As someone worried about binding and exercise, I want to see clear “today we adjusted volume because you are binding” messages, so I understand how the app is protecting me.
7. As a user planning to reduce binding during workouts, I want suggestions for lower dysphoria options (compression tops, layering, etc.), so I don’t feel like my only choices are “bind dangerously” or “do nothing.”

### 6.3 Pre-top surgery prep

8. As a person preparing for top surgery, I want a pre-op training path that focuses on building general strength, stamina, and mobility, so I feel physically ready for surgery and recovery.
9. As someone anxious about surgery, I want the app to set realistic expectations about what training can and cannot change before surgery, so I don’t blame myself for outcomes outside my control.

### 6.4 Post-top surgery return to movement

10. As a user 4–12 weeks post top surgery, I want a phased return-to-movement outline that shows what types of movement are usually appropriate at my stage, so I have a starting point to discuss with my surgeon and adjust from.
11. As a post-op user, I want workouts that clearly avoid movements that are typically too risky in my current phase (heavy pressing, overhead loading, etc.), so I don’t accidentally pick exercises that contradict my restrictions.
12. As someone afraid of “ruining my results,” I want gentle explanations attached to my plan that explain why certain movements are delayed or restricted, so I can be patient and feel reassured.

### 6.5 HRT-aware programming

13. As a user early on T, I want to see realistic expectations about strength and muscle gains, so I don’t feel like I’m “failing” if progress is slower than fitness influencers.
14. As someone on HRT, I want my workout plan to adjust volume and recovery over time based on my phase, so my plan feels like it evolves with my body rather than being static.
15. As a user feeling extra fatigue during HRT adjustments, I want the app to validate that this can happen and suggest lighter options or extra rest, so I feel supported instead of weak.

### 6.6 Space & environment

16. As a user who feels unsafe in locker rooms, I want home-first and minimal-equipment options, so I can build strength without relying on gyms.
17. As someone with access to a gym but high anxiety, I want workouts that can be done without using the locker room (arrive changed, minimal equipment circuits), so I can still benefit from gym access.
18. As a user whose environment changes (for example I join a queer gym later), I want to update my training environment and equipment easily, so my plan grows with my access.

### 6.7 Education & reassurance

19. As a user with anxiety about safety, I want a simple “Why this workout?” explanation that tells me what the app considered (binding, HRT, surgery, environment), so I can trust the plan.
20. As someone used to doomscrolling Reddit for answers, I want short, trustworthy education snippets inside the app (binder safety, post-op basics, HRT expectations), so I can stop bouncing between tabs.
21. As a user who worries I’m “doing it wrong,” I want guidance on what normal discomfort vs. concerning symptoms feel like (without diagnosing), so I know when to rest and when to seek care.

### 6.8 Copilot (if included in MVP)

22. As a user, I want to ask free-form questions like “Is it okay to do this workout while binding today?” and get an answer that combines research and my own profile, so I feel personally supported.
23. As someone recovering from surgery, I want Copilot to remind me to follow my surgeon’s instructions and not override them with generic advice, so I’m not tempted to ignore medical guidance.
24. As a user with ADHD, I want to ask Copilot for simple, practical adjustments (“What’s a shorter version of today’s workout?”) so I can still do *something* on low-executive-function days.

### 6.9 Consistency, motivation, and reflection

25. As a user who struggles with consistency, I want the app to celebrate small wins (for example consistent walks, partial workouts), so I don’t feel like it’s “all or nothing.”
26. As someone whose dysphoria and mood fluctuate, I want optional quick check-ins (“How did moving today feel in your body?”), so I can see patterns in what types of movement help me feel better.
27. As a user who may or may not stay on T or may change plans, I want the app to flex if my path changes, so I don’t feel like I “broke” the program by making new decisions about my body.

