7. Success Metrics for MVP

MVP success is about trust, safety, and “this finally gets me” more than it is about raw MAUs. Metrics are split into four buckets.

7.1 Adoption and activation

Goal: Prove that the right people can discover, onboard, and reach their first safe workout.

MVP cohort size

Target: 30 to 100 transmasc or NB users in the first closed beta

Source: personal network, r/transfitness volunteers, community groups

Onboarding completion rate

Definition: Percentage of users who start onboarding and finish the last question

Target: 75 percent or higher

Interpretation: If it is lower, questions feel confusing, intrusive, or too long

First workout generation rate

Definition: Percentage of onboarded users who successfully generate at least one workout

Target: 80 percent or higher

Interpretation: Confirms the generator is usable and not intimidating

7.2 Engagement and early retention

Goal: Prove that people actually use the workouts and feel good about them, not just poke around.

Workout start rate

Definition: Percentage of generated workouts that are opened and started

Target: 60 percent or higher for the first two weeks of a cohort

Workout completion rate

Definition: Percentage of started workouts that are marked complete

Target: 50 percent or higher

Short term retention

Definition: Percentage of users who complete at least three workouts in their first fourteen days

Target: 40 percent or higher

Feature usage: “Why this workout”

Definition: Percentage of workout sessions where the user opens the “Why this workout” explanation

Target: 50 percent or higher in early cohorts

Interpretation: High usage means people actually care about the safety and reasoning, which is your wedge

7.3 Trust, perceived safety, and product market fit

Goal: Confirm that the core value lands for the right users.

Collect this via short in app surveys or follow up forms.

Perceived safety score

Question: “On a scale of 1 to 5, how safe do you feel following the workouts in TransFitness, given your binding, HRT, and surgery context?”

Target: Average 4.0 or higher

Relevance score

Question: “On a scale of 1 to 5, how well do you feel this app understands your situation compared to general fitness apps?”

Target: Average 4.0 or higher

“Would you be sad if this went away” metric

Question: “If you could no longer use TransFitness, how disappointed would you be?”

Options: Very, somewhat, not really

Target: At least 40 percent answering “Very disappointed” in the target persona

Qualitative signal

Look for phrases like:

“I have never seen an app ask me these questions”

“I feel safer doing this than random YouTube stuff”

“I finally see my situation reflected in the plan”

These matter more than vanity metrics at MVP.

7.4 Safety and operational metrics

Goal: Make sure you are not accidentally doing harm or wandering into doctor cosplay.

Red flag deflection adherence

Definition: Percentage of red flag questions where Copilot or static content correctly deflects to “seek medical care, follow your surgeon”

Target: 100 percent

How: Spot check Copilot logs for any messages tagged with high risk

Zero “the app told me to ignore my doctor” incidents

Target: 0 reports in feedback channels

Crash free sessions

Target: 95 percent or higher crash free rate during beta

Bug threshold

Target: No critical bugs that corrupt user data, misapply core safety rules, or prevent workout generation

